To correctly use ImageDrawText in your DialogWindow class, you need to provide all the required parameters. Here's the correct way to fill in the ImageDrawText parameters:

```cpp
#pragma once
#include "raylib.h"
#include <string>

class DialogWindow {
public:
    int x;
    int y;
    int width;
    int height;
    std::string text;

    DialogWindow(int posX, int posY, int windowWidth, int windowHeight, std::string textString){
        x = posX; // Note: Fixed assignment direction
        y = posY;
        width = windowWidth;
        height = windowHeight;
        text = textString;

        // Load the dialog window image
        Image dialog_rec = LoadImage("sprites/dialogwindow.png");
        // Draw text on the image
        ImageDrawText(&dialog_rec,          // Image pointer
                     text.c_str(),          // Convert std::string to const char*
                     x,                     // X position
                     y,                     // Y position
                     20,                    // Font size (adjust as needed)
                     BLACK);                // Text color
    }

private:
    Image dialog_rec;
};
```

Key points to note:

1. ImageDrawText needs a pointer to the Image as its first parameter
2. The text needs to be converted from std::string to const char* using .c_str()
3. The assignments in your constructor were reversed (they should be x = posX, not posX = x)
4. ImageDrawText should typically be called after the image is loaded
5. You might want to make dialog_rec a private member variable

Also, make sure to properly unload the image when you're done with it (you might want to add a destructor):

```cpp
~DialogWindow() {
    UnloadImage(dialog_rec);
}
```

If you want to update the text dynamically, you might want to create a separate method:

```cpp
void UpdateText(const std::string& newText) {
    text = newText;
    ImageDrawText(&dialog_rec, 
                 text.c_str(), 
                 x, 
                 y, 
                 20, 
                 BLACK);
}
```
